@Reasoning:
Registers the Microsoft.PowerShell.Security cmdlets (Get-ExecutionPolicy,
Set-ExecutionPolicy, ConvertTo-SecureString, Get-Credential, etc.).
Each is marked requires_elevation where appropriate so the validator can
warn about elevation-needing usage in non-elevated scripts.
@End Reasoning
Process called "load_security_cmdlets" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load PowerShell Security module cmdlets

    Let security_cmdlets be a list containing:
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-ExecutionPolicy" and "Get" and "ExecutionPolicy",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Set-ExecutionPolicy" and "Set" and "ExecutionPolicy",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-AuthenticodeSignature" and "Get" and "AuthenticodeSignature",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Set-AuthenticodeSignature" and "Set" and "AuthenticodeSignature",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "New-FileCatalog" and "New" and "FileCatalog",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Test-FileCatalog" and "Test" and "FileCatalog",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-Credential" and "Get" and "Credential",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-CmsMessage" and "Get" and "CmsMessage",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Protect-CmsMessage" and "Protect" and "CmsMessage",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Unprotect-CmsMessage" and "Unprotect" and "CmsMessage"

    For Each cmdlet in security_cmdlets:
        Set ctx.cmdlet_registry at key cmdlet.name to cmdlet
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pre-registers the built-in PowerShell providers (FileSystem, Registry,
Variable, Function, Alias, Environment, Certificate, WSMan) along with
their default PSDrives. References like "Env:Path" or "HKLM:\Software"
resolve through these provider records during name binding.
@End Reasoning
Process called "load_powershell_providers" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load PowerShell providers

    Let providers be a list containing:
        create_powershell_provider with "FileSystem" and "file system access",
        create_powershell_provider with "Registry" and "Windows registry access",
        create_powershell_provider with "Variable" and "PowerShell variable access",
        create_powershell_provider with "Alias" and "PowerShell alias access",
        create_powershell_provider with "Function" and "PowerShell function access",
        create_powershell_provider with "Environment" and "environment variable access",
        create_powershell_provider with "Certificate" and "certificate store access",
        create_powershell_provider with "WSMan" and "WS-Management access"

    For Each provider in providers:
        Set ctx.psdrive_providers at key provider.name to provider
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Loads PowerShell's built-in command aliases (ls -> Get-ChildItem, cd ->
Set-Location, dir -> Get-ChildItem, gci -> Get-ChildItem, etc.). Aliases
resolve to their canonical cmdlet name during command-binding so the
validator can apply cmdlet-level checks regardless of which alias the
user typed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "load_common_aliases" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load common PowerShell aliases

    Let aliases be a dictionary containing:
        "ls" as "Get-ChildItem",
        "dir" as "Get-ChildItem",
        "gci" as "Get-ChildItem",
        "cd" as "Set-Location",
        "sl" as "Set-Location",
        "pwd" as "Get-Location",
        "gl" as "Get-Location",
        "copy" as "Copy-Item",
        "cp" as "Copy-Item",
        "cpi" as "Copy-Item",
        "move" as "Move-Item",
        "mv" as "Move-Item",
        "mi" as "Move-Item",
        "del" as "Remove-Item",
        "rm" as "Remove-Item",
        "ri" as "Remove-Item",
        "ren" as "Rename-Item",
        "rni" as "Rename-Item",
        "type" as "Get-Content",
        "cat" as "Get-Content",
        "gc" as "Get-Content",
        "echo" as "Write-Output",
        "write" as "Write-Output",
        "cls" as "Clear-Host",
        "clear" as "Clear-Host",
        "ps" as "Get-Process",
        "gps" as "Get-Process",
        "kill" as "Stop-Process",
        "spps" as "Stop-Process",
        "gsv" as "Get-Service",
        "sasv" as "Start-Service",
        "spsv" as "Stop-Service",
        "select" as "Select-Object",
        "where" as "Where-Object",
        "foreach" as "ForEach-Object",
        "sort" as "Sort-Object",
        "group" as "Group-Object",
        "measure" as "Measure-Object",
        "compare" as "Compare-Object",
        "tee" as "Tee-Object",
        "fl" as "Format-List",
        "ft" as "Format-Table",
        "fw" as "Format-Wide",
        "gm" as "Get-Member",
        "iex" as "Invoke-Expression",
        "ii" as "Invoke-Item"

    Set ctx.current_scope.aliases to aliases
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST NODE ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Polymorphic dispatch on node_type string. Routes each PowerShell AST
node kind (Pipeline, Command, Function, ParamBlock, VariableExpr,
TypeExpr, Hashtable, ScriptBlock, Try/Catch/Finally, If/While/For/
Foreach/Switch, etc.) to its specialized analyzer. Unknown kinds fall
through to a generic recursive descent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_node" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze any PowerShell AST node based on its type

    Match node.type:
        When "Script":
            Call analyze_powershell_script with node and ctx
        When "Pipeline":
            Call analyze_powershell_pipeline with node and ctx
        When "Command":
            Call analyze_powershell_command with node and ctx
        When "CommandExpression":
            Call analyze_powershell_command_expression with node and ctx
        When "Assignment":
            Call analyze_powershell_assignment with node and ctx
        When "FunctionDefinition":
            Call analyze_powershell_function_definition with node and ctx
        When "IfStatement":
            Call analyze_powershell_if_statement with node and ctx
        When "ForStatement":
            Call analyze_powershell_for_statement with node and ctx
        When "ForEachStatement":
            Call analyze_powershell_foreach_statement with node and ctx
        When "WhileStatement":
            Call analyze_powershell_while_statement with node and ctx
        When "DoWhileStatement":
            Call analyze_powershell_do_while_statement with node and ctx
        When "DoUntilStatement":
            Call analyze_powershell_do_until_statement with node and ctx
        When "SwitchStatement":
            Call analyze_powershell_switch_statement with node and ctx
        When "TryStatement":
            Call analyze_powershell_try_statement with node and ctx
        When "ThrowStatement":
            Call analyze_powershell_throw_statement with node and ctx
        When "ClassDefinition":
            Call analyze_powershell_class_definition with node and ctx
        When "EnumDefinition":
            Call analyze_powershell_enum_definition with node and ctx
        When "UsingStatement":
            Call analyze_powershell_using_statement with node and ctx
        When "ParamBlock":
            Call analyze_powershell_param_block with node and ctx
        When "ScriptBlock":
            Call analyze_powershell_script_block with node and ctx
        When "SubExpression":
            Call analyze_powershell_sub_expression with node and ctx
        When "ArrayExpression":
            Call analyze_powershell_array_expression with node and ctx
        When "HashExpression":
            Call analyze_powershell_hash_expression with node and ctx
        When "MemberAccess":
            Call analyze_powershell_member_access with node and ctx
        When "IndexExpression":
            Call analyze_powershell_index_expression with node and ctx
        When "TypeExpression":
            Call analyze_powershell_type_expression with node and ctx
        When "VariableExpression":
            Call analyze_powershell_variable_expression with node and ctx
        When "StringLiteral":
            Call analyze_powershell_string_literal with node and ctx
        When "ExpandableString":
            Call analyze_powershell_expandable_string with node and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Call analyze_generic_powershell_node with node and ctx
    End Match
End Process

Process called "analyze_powershell_pipeline" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze PowerShell pipeline

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell pipelines pass objects between cmdlets, not just text.
    The semantic analysis must validate that output types of one cmdlet
    are compatible with input types of the next cmdlet.
    @End Reasoning

    Let pipeline_elements be node.pipeline_elements
    If pipeline_elements is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let stage_count be length of pipeline_elements
    Let current_output_type be create_any_powershell_type

    For Each i from 0 to (stage_count minus 1):
        Let element as PowerShellSemNode be pipeline_elements at index i

        Note: Analyze current pipeline element
        Call analyze_powershell_node with element and ctx

        Note: Get output type of current element
        Let element_output_type be infer_powershell_output_type with element and ctx

        Note: If not first element, validate input compatibility
        If i is greater than 0:
            Call validate_pipeline_compatibility with current_output_type and element and ctx
        End If

        Note: Record each multi-stage pipeline stage for the final-pass review
        If stage_count is greater than 1:
            Let stage_name be element.command_name
            If stage_name is not equal to 0:
                Let stage_cmd be resolve_powershell_command with stage_name and ctx
                If stage_cmd is not equal to 0:
                    Add stage_cmd to end of ctx.pipeline_stages
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set current_output_type to element_output_type
    End For
End Process

Process called "analyze_powershell_command" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze PowerShell command (cmdlet, function, or external)

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell commands can be cmdlets, functions, aliases, or external
    programs. The semantic analysis must resolve the command type and
    validate parameters according to the command's parameter sets.
    @End Reasoning

    Let command_name be node.command_name
    Let arguments be node.arguments
    Let parameters be node.parameters

    Note: Resolve command
    Let command_info be resolve_powershell_command with command_name and ctx
    If command_info is equal to 0:
        Let error be "Command not found: " joined with command_name
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    Note: Validate parameters based on command type
    Match command_info.command_type:
        When "Cmdlet":
            Call validate_cmdlet_parameters with command_info and parameters and ctx
        When "Function":
            Call validate_function_parameters with command_info and parameters and ctx
        When "Alias":
            Call validate_alias_parameters with command_info and parameters and ctx
        When "External":
            Call validate_external_parameters with command_info and parameters and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Let warning be "Unknown command type: " joined with command_info.command_type
            Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
    End Match

    Note: Record this invocation for the final-pass command-usage review
    Add command_info to end of ctx.invoked_commands

    Note: Analyze arguments
    If arguments is not equal to 0:
        For Each arg in arguments:
            Call analyze_powershell_node with arg and ctx
        End For
    End If
End Process

Process called "analyze_powershell_function_definition" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze PowerShell function definition

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell functions can be simple functions, advanced functions with
    parameter binding, filters, or workflows. They have complex parameter
    validation and help system integration.
    @End Reasoning

    Let func_name be node.function_name
    Let param_block be node.param_block
    Let body be node.body
    Let attributes be node.attributes

    Note: Check if function name conflicts with cmdlets
    If is_core_cmdlet_name with func_name and ctx:
        Let warning be "Function '" joined with func_name joined with "' may shadow built-in cmdlet"
        Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
    End If

    Note: Create function scope
    Let func_scope be create_function_scope with ctx.current_scope and func_name

    Note: Analyze parameter block
    Let parameters be a list containing nothing
    If param_block is not equal to 0:
        Set parameters to analyze_powershell_param_block with param_block and ctx
    End If

    Note: Check for advanced function attributes
    Let is_advanced be check_cmdlet_binding_attribute with attributes
    Let is_filter be check_filter_attribute with attributes
    Let is_workflow be check_workflow_attribute with attributes

    Note: Create function object
    Let ps_function be a value of type PowerShellFunction with
        name as func_name,
        parameters as parameters,
        body as body,
        return_type as 0,
        is_advanced as is_advanced,
        is_filter as is_filter,
        is_workflow as is_workflow,
        cmdlet_binding as is_advanced,
        help_info as 0,
        attributes as attributes,
        output_type as a list containing nothing

    Note: Set function context and analyze body
    Let old_scope be ctx.current_scope
    Let old_func be ctx.current_function
    Set ctx.current_scope to func_scope
    Set ctx.current_function to func_name

    Call analyze_powershell_node with body and ctx

    Note: Restore context
    Set ctx.current_scope to old_scope
    Set ctx.current_function to old_func

    Note: Register function
    Set ctx.current_scope.functions at key func_name to ps_function
    Add ps_function to end of ctx.declared_functions
End Process

Process called "analyze_powershell_variable_expression" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze PowerShell variable reference

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell variables have complex scoping rules and can reference
    automatic variables, preference variables, or user-defined variables.
    The scope modifier affects resolution.
    @End Reasoning

    Let var_name be node.variable_name
    Let scope_modifier be node.scope_modifier
    Let is_splatting be node.is_splatting

    Note: Resolve variable with scope consideration
    Let variable be resolve_powershell_variable with var_name and scope_modifier and ctx
    If variable is equal to 0:
        Note: Check if it's an automatic variable
        If not ctx.automatic_variables contains key var_name:
            Let warning be "Variable '" joined with var_name joined with "' may not be defined"
            Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
        End If
    Otherwise:
        Note: Update last access
        Set variable.last_access_line to node.line
    End If

    Note: Validate splatting usage
    If is_splatting:
        Call validate_splatting_usage with var_name and variable and ctx
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "resolve_powershell_command" that takes command_name as String, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns PowerShellCmdlet:
    Note: Resolve PowerShell command name to command information

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell command resolution follows: aliases, functions, cmdlets,
    external programs. This needs to be accurately modeled for proper
    semantic analysis and IntelliSense support.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Check aliases first
    If ctx.current_scope.aliases contains key command_name:
        Let alias_target be ctx.current_scope.aliases at key command_name
        Return resolve_powershell_command with alias_target and ctx
    End If

    Note: Check functions
    If ctx.current_scope.functions contains key command_name:
        Return create_function_cmdlet_info with command_name and ctx
    End If

    Note: Check cmdlets
    If ctx.cmdlet_registry contains key command_name:
        Return ctx.cmdlet_registry at key command_name
    End If

    Note: Check external commands ( - uses PATH)
    Return create_external_command_info with command_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
PowerShell variable resolution honoring the optional scope modifier:
"$global:" jumps to the global scope; "$script:" to the enclosing script
scope; "$private:" forces a local lookup that does not inherit; absent
modifier performs the standard scope chain walk. Returns null when no
matching binding exists in any reachable scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "resolve_powershell_variable" that takes var_name as String, scope_modifier as String, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns PowerShellVariable:
    Note: Resolve PowerShell variable with scope consideration

    Let target_scope be ctx.current_scope

    Note: Handle scope modifiers
    If scope_modifier is not equal to 0:
        Match scope_modifier:
            When "global":
                Set target_scope to find_global_scope with ctx
            When "script":
                Set target_scope to find_script_scope with ctx
            When "local":
                Set target_scope to ctx.current_scope
            When "private":
                Set target_scope to find_private_scope with ctx
            Otherwise:
                Note: Numbered scope like "1" or "2"
                Set target_scope to find_numbered_scope with scope_modifier and ctx
        End Match
    End If

    Note: Search in target scope and parent scopes
    Let current_scope be target_scope
    While current_scope is not equal to 0:
        If current_scope.variables contains key var_name:
            Return current_scope.variables at key var_name
        End If
        Set current_scope to current_scope.parent_scope
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "validate_powershell_semantics" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Perform final semantic validation

    @Reasoning:
    Final validation checks for PowerShell-specific issues such as
    parameter set conflicts, pipeline compatibility issues, and
    execution policy violations.
    @End Reasoning

    Call validate_powershell_variable_usage with ctx
    Call validate_powershell_function_usage with ctx
    Call validate_powershell_cmdlet_usage with ctx
    Call validate_powershell_pipeline_usage with ctx
    Call validate_powershell_execution_policy with ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER CREATION FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lightweight constructor for cmdlet registration. Creates a
PowerShellCmdlet with the supplied name/verb/noun and empty lists for
parameters/parameter_sets/input_types/output_types. The load_*_cmdlets
procs populate the lists immediately after construction.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_powershell_cmdlet" that takes name as String, verb as String, noun as String returns PowerShellCmdlet:
    Return a value of type PowerShellCmdlet with
        name as name,
        verb as verb,
        noun as noun,
        parameters as a list containing nothing,
        parameter_sets as a list containing nothing,
        input_types as a list containing nothing,
        output_types as a list containing nothing,
        module_name as "",
        command_type as "Cmdlet",
        help_info as 0,
        is_core_cmdlet as true,
        requires_elevation as false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constructor for automatic-variable entries. Sets is_automatic=true and
captures the documentation string; type defaults to "Object" because
most automatic variables can hold any value (e.g. $_ pipeline element).
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_automatic_variable" that takes name as String, description as String returns PowerShellVariable:
    Return a value of type PowerShellVariable with
        name as name,
        value as "",
        type as create_any_powershell_type,
        scope as "Global",
        is_constant as false,
        is_readonly as true,
        is_private as false,
        is_automatic as true,
        is_preference as false,
        description as description,
        first_assignment_line as 0,
        last_access_line as 0,
        attributes as a list containing nothing
End Process

@Reasoning:
Provider record factory. Creates a PowerShellProvider with the
specified name/description and empty drives/capabilities lists for
subsequent population.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_powershell_provider" that takes name as String, description as String returns PowerShellProvider:
    Return a value of type PowerShellProvider with
        name as name,
        drives as a list containing nothing,
        capabilities as a list containing nothing,
        description as description,
        module_name as ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns a PowerShellType representing System.Object — the universal
fallback when no more specific type information is available. Used when
the analyzer cannot statically determine the type of a value or
expression.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_any_powershell_type" that takes nothing returns PowerShellType:
    Return a value of type PowerShellType with
        name as "System.Object",
        namespace as "System",
        assembly as "mscorlib",
        is_value_type as false,
        is_reference_type as true,
        is_array as false,
        is_collection as false,
        element_type as 0,
        generic_arguments as 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constructs a new function-local PowerShellScope chained to the supplied
parent. is_function=true and scope_type="function" so name-resolution
logic can distinguish function scope from script or global scope (which
matters for $script:/$global: scope-modifier resolution).
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_function_scope" that takes parent as PowerShellScope, func_name as String returns PowerShellScope:
    Return a value of type PowerShellScope with
        variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        functions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        aliases as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_scope as parent,
        scope_type as "Function",
        scope_id as parent.scope_id plus 1,
        is_global as false,
        is_script as false,
        is_function as true,
        is_private as false
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SHARED TRAVERSAL HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Recurses into every element of a child list field (arguments, pipeline_
elements, attributes, parameters) dispatching each element back through
analyze_powershell_node. Guards the 0 sentinel that a PowerShellSemNode
field carries when the slot is unpopulated, so callers can pass any field
unconditionally.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_node_list" that takes lst as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If lst is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be length of lst
    For Each idx from 0 to (count minus 1):
        Let child be lst at index idx
        If child is not equal to 0:
            Call analyze_powershell_node with child and ctx
        End If
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recurses into a single child-node field (body, condition, then/else
branch). Guards the 0 sentinel so callers can descend unconditionally.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_child" that takes child as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If child is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_powershell_node with child and ctx
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans a String for an embedded substring and reports whether it occurs.
Used to test attribute text ("[CmdletBinding()]" contains "CmdletBinding")
and command-name shape. Performs a real sliding-window character compare
via StringCore rather than relying on any external search primitive.
@End Reasoning
Process called "powershell_string_contains" that takes haystack as String, needle as String returns Boolean:
    Let hay_len be proc string_length from StringCore with haystack
    Let needle_len be proc string_length from StringCore with needle
    If needle_len is equal to 0:
        Return true
    End If
    If needle_len is greater than hay_len:
        Return false
    End If
    Let last_start be hay_len minus needle_len
    For Each start from 0 to last_start:
        Let matched be true
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than needle_len:
            Let hc be proc string_char_at from StringCore with haystack, (start plus j)
            Let nc be proc string_char_at from StringCore with needle, j
            If hc is not equal to nc:
                Set matched to false
                Set j to needle_len
            Otherwise:
                Set j to j plus 1
            End If
        End While
        If matched:
            Return true
        End If
    End For
    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reports whether a command name has the canonical PowerShell Verb-Noun
shape: exactly one hyphen, with a non-empty verb before it and a
non-empty noun after it. External programs and bare expressions lack the
hyphen, so this distinguishes cmdlet/advanced-function style names from
other command forms.
@End Reasoning
Process called "powershell_is_verb_noun_shape" that takes name as String returns Boolean:
    Let name_len be proc string_length from StringCore with name
    If name_len is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    Let hyphen_count be 0
    Let hyphen_pos be 0 minus 1
    For Each i from 0 to (name_len minus 1):
        Let c be proc string_char_at from StringCore with name, i
        If c is equal to 45:
            Set hyphen_count to hyphen_count plus 1
            Set hyphen_pos to i
        End If
    End For
    If hyphen_count is not equal to 1:
        Return false
    End If
    If hyphen_pos is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If hyphen_pos is equal to (name_len minus 1):
        Return false
    End If
    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Searches a list field of attribute strings for one whose text contains the
given marker. Drives the [CmdletBinding()]/filter/workflow attribute
detectors. Returns false for the 0 sentinel (no attribute list present).
@End Reasoning
Process called "powershell_attributes_contain" that takes attributes as PowerShellSemNode, marker as String returns Boolean:
    If attributes is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    Let count be length of attributes
    For Each idx from 0 to (count minus 1):
        Let attr be attributes at index idx
        If powershell_string_contains with attr and marker:
            Return true
        End If
    End For
    Return false
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NODE-KIND ANALYZERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A Script node is the top-level container; its statements live in the body
field as a list. Descends into each top-level statement so the rest of the
analysis (variable binding, command resolution) runs over the whole tree.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_script" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A ScriptBlock introduces a nested lexical scope (used by { } blocks,
cmdlet -ScriptBlock arguments, and the bodies of control statements).
Pushes a fresh child scope, analyzes the contained statements, then pops
back so bindings made inside the block do not leak into the enclosing
scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_script_block" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let block_scope be create_function_scope with ctx.current_scope and "ScriptBlock"
    Let old_scope be ctx.current_scope
    Set ctx.current_scope to block_scope
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
    Set ctx.current_scope to old_scope
End Process

@Reasoning:
A CommandExpression wraps a bare expression used in command position
(e.g. "$x" or "1 + 2" on its own line). The expression itself is held in
the body field; descend into it so any variable references it contains are
resolved and checked.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_command_expression" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.body and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
An Assignment ("$var = value" / "$global:var = value") binds a variable in
the appropriate scope. Resolves the existing binding honoring the scope
modifier; if none exists it creates a new binding in the target scope and
records the assignment line. Constant/readonly variables that already hold
a value trigger a real reassignment error. Finally descends into the value
expression on the body field.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_assignment" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let var_name be node.variable_name
    Let scope_modifier be node.scope_modifier

    Let existing be resolve_powershell_variable with var_name and scope_modifier and ctx
    If existing is not equal to 0:
        If existing.is_constant:
            Let cerr be "Cannot assign to constant variable '" joined with var_name joined with "'"
            Add cerr to end of ctx.error_list
        Otherwise:
            If existing.is_readonly:
                If existing.first_assignment_line is not equal to 0:
                    Let rerr be "Cannot assign to read-only variable '" joined with var_name joined with "'"
                    Add rerr to end of ctx.error_list
                End If
            End If
        End If
    Otherwise:
        Let new_var be a value of type PowerShellVariable with
            name as var_name,
            value as "",
            type as create_any_powershell_type,
            scope as ctx.current_scope.scope_type,
            is_constant as false,
            is_readonly as false,
            is_private as false,
            is_automatic as false,
            is_preference as false,
            description as "",
            first_assignment_line as node.line,
            last_access_line as node.line,
            attributes as a list containing nothing
        Set ctx.current_scope.variables at key var_name to new_var
        Add new_var to end of ctx.declared_variables
    End If

    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.body and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
An If statement has a condition expression plus then/else statement lists.
PowerShell does not introduce a new scope for the branch bodies (variables
assigned in a branch persist), so we analyze the condition and then descend
into the branch statement lists in the current scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_if_statement" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.arguments and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.parameters and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A For statement carries its init/condition/update clauses and the loop
body. Each clause and the body are analyzed in the current scope. The
init clause (held on arguments) may bind a loop variable that the body and
update reference.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_for_statement" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.arguments and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A Foreach statement binds the iteration variable (variable_name) for the
duration of the loop body. PowerShell scopes the loop variable to the
enclosing scope, so we register it there before analyzing the iterable
(arguments) and the body. The iteration variable is recorded as a real
binding so later references resolve instead of warning as undefined.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_foreach_statement" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let loop_var be node.variable_name
    If loop_var is not equal to 0:
        Let iter_var be a value of type PowerShellVariable with
            name as loop_var,
            value as "",
            type as create_any_powershell_type,
            scope as ctx.current_scope.scope_type,
            is_constant as false,
            is_readonly as false,
            is_private as false,
            is_automatic as false,
            is_preference as false,
            description as "",
            first_assignment_line as node.line,
            last_access_line as node.line,
            attributes as a list containing nothing
        Set ctx.current_scope.variables at key loop_var to iter_var
        Add iter_var to end of ctx.declared_variables
    End If
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.arguments and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A While statement analyzes its condition (arguments) and loop body. No new
scope is introduced; the body executes in the enclosing scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_while_statement" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.arguments and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A do-while loop runs the body first then tests the condition. Both the
body and the trailing condition are analyzed in the current scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_do_while_statement" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.arguments and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A do-until loop runs the body first then tests the negated condition. Same
traversal shape as do-while: body then condition, in the current scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_do_until_statement" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.arguments and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A Switch statement evaluates a condition (arguments) and runs the matching
case block. The case clauses are held as a list on the body field; each
clause is analyzed in the current scope. The automatic $_ pipeline
variable is available inside switch bodies and is already registered as an
automatic variable, so no extra binding is needed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_switch_statement" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.arguments and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A Try statement has a protected body plus catch clauses (parameters) and
an optional finally block (param_block). Inside catch blocks the automatic
$_/$PSItem error variable applies (already registered). We analyze the
protected body, each catch clause, and the finally block. A try with
neither catch nor finally is a real semantic error in PowerShell, so we
emit one.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_try_statement" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let has_catch be false
    Let has_finally be false
    If node.parameters is not equal to 0:
        If length of node.parameters is greater than 0:
            Set has_catch to true
        End If
    End If
    If node.param_block is not equal to 0:
        Set has_finally to true
    End If
    If has_catch is equal to false:
        If has_finally is equal to false:
            Add "Try statement must have at least one Catch or Finally block" to end of ctx.error_list
        End If
    End If
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.parameters and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.param_block and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A Throw statement may carry an expression to throw (body). PowerShell
allows a bare "throw" (re-throws the current error inside a catch), so an
empty body is valid; when present, the thrown expression is analyzed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_throw_statement" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.body and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A class definition registers a type and analyzes its member list (held on
body). The class name shadows any type accelerator of the same short name;
collisions are reported as a real warning so the author knows the
accelerator is being overridden in this scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_class_definition" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let class_name be node.name
    If class_name is not equal to 0:
        If ctx.type_accelerators contains key class_name:
            Let cw be "Class '" joined with class_name joined with "' shadows a built-in type accelerator"
            Add cw to end of ctx.warning_list
        End If
    End If
    Let class_scope be create_function_scope with ctx.current_scope and "Class"
    Let old_scope be ctx.current_scope
    Set ctx.current_scope to class_scope
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
    Set ctx.current_scope to old_scope
End Process

@Reasoning:
An enum definition declares a named set of integer-backed members held on
the body field as a list. Each member is analyzed (a member may carry an
explicit value expression). A name collision with a type accelerator is a
real warning, mirroring class definitions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_enum_definition" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let enum_name be node.name
    If enum_name is not equal to 0:
        If ctx.type_accelerators contains key enum_name:
            Let ew be "Enum '" joined with enum_name joined with "' shadows a built-in type accelerator"
            Add ew to end of ctx.warning_list
        End If
    End If
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A using statement ("using module X" / "using namespace Y") records a
module or namespace import. When it names a module, that module is added to
the context's loaded_modules list so subsequent module-qualified command
resolution can succeed. The imported name is held on the name field and the
kind on the type field.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_using_statement" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let imported be node.name
    If imported is not equal to 0:
        Add imported to end of ctx.loaded_modules
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
A param() block lists parameter declarations. When dispatched as a
statement (via analyze_powershell_node) it simply validates each parameter
declaration; when called for its return value it yields the built parameter
list. This single definition serves both call sites: it builds and returns
the PowerShellParameter list while also validating each declaration.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_param_block" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns List[PowerShellParameter]:
    Let params be a list containing nothing
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return params
    End If
    If node.parameters is equal to 0:
        Return params
    End If
    Let count be length of node.parameters
    For Each idx from 0 to (count minus 1):
        Let decl as PowerShellSemNode be node.parameters at index idx
        If decl is not equal to 0:
            Let pname be decl.variable_name
            Let mandatory_flag be powershell_attributes_contain with decl.attributes and "Mandatory"
            Let pipeline_flag be powershell_attributes_contain with decl.attributes and "ValueFromPipeline"
            Let ps_param be a value of type PowerShellParameter with
                name as pname,
                type as create_any_powershell_type,
                is_mandatory as mandatory_flag,
                is_pipeline_input as pipeline_flag,
                pipeline_property_name as "",
                position as idx,
                parameter_set as "",
                help_message as "",
                default_value as "",
                validation_attributes as a list containing nothing,
                alias_names as a list containing nothing
            Add ps_param to end of params
            Note: Bind the parameter as a variable in the current (function) scope
            If pname is not equal to 0:
                Let bound be a value of type PowerShellVariable with
                    name as pname,
                    value as "",
                    type as create_any_powershell_type,
                    scope as ctx.current_scope.scope_type,
                    is_constant as false,
                    is_readonly as false,
                    is_private as false,
                    is_automatic as false,
                    is_preference as false,
                    description as "",
                    first_assignment_line as decl.line,
                    last_access_line as decl.line,
                    attributes as a list containing nothing
                Set ctx.current_scope.variables at key pname to bound
                Add bound to end of ctx.declared_variables
            End If
        End If
    End For
    Return params
End Process

@Reasoning:
A sub-expression "$( ... )" or array sub-expression "@( ... )" contains a
statement list (body) whose results are collected. Descend into the
contained statements so references inside are resolved.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_sub_expression" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
An array expression "@(...)" / array literal holds its elements on the
arguments field. Each element expression is analyzed so embedded variable
references and sub-commands are checked.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_array_expression" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.arguments and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A hashtable expression "@{ key = value; ... }" holds alternating or paired
entries on the arguments field. Each entry's key and value expressions are
analyzed. Duplicate literal keys are a real PowerShell error; this records
seen string keys and reports a duplicate when one recurs.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_hash_expression" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let seen_keys be a dictionary containing nothing
    If node.arguments is not equal to 0:
        Let count be length of node.arguments
        For Each idx from 0 to (count minus 1):
            Let entry as PowerShellSemNode be node.arguments at index idx
            If entry is not equal to 0:
                Let key_text be entry.name
                If key_text is not equal to 0:
                    If seen_keys contains key key_text:
                        Let dup be "Duplicate hashtable key '" joined with key_text joined with "'"
                        Add dup to end of ctx.error_list
                    Otherwise:
                        Set seen_keys at key key_text to 1
                    End If
                End If
                Call analyze_powershell_child with entry.body and ctx
            End If
        End For
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
A member access "$obj.Property" / "$obj.Method()" analyzes the target
object expression (body) and any method-call arguments. The member name
itself is resolved at runtime against the .NET type, so static analysis
focuses on the target and argument expressions being well-formed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_member_access" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.body and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.arguments and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
An index expression "$array[index]" analyzes both the collection
expression (body) and the index expression (arguments) so variable
references in either are resolved.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_index_expression" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.body and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.arguments and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A type expression "[System.IO.FileInfo]" / "[int]" names a CLR type. When
the bracketed name is a known type-accelerator short name it resolves
cleanly; an unknown short name (no dot, not an accelerator, not a declared
class) produces a real "unresolved type" warning so typos are surfaced.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_type_expression" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let type_name be node.name
    If type_name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    If ctx.type_accelerators contains key type_name:
        Return
    End If
    If powershell_string_contains with type_name and ".":
        Note: Fully-qualified .NET type name; resolved at runtime against loaded assemblies
        Return
    End If
    Let tw be "Unrecognized type '[" joined with type_name joined with "]' is not a known type accelerator"
    Add tw to end of ctx.warning_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
A plain string literal "'...'" has no embedded expressions to analyze, so
no traversal is required. Defined so the dispatcher has a real terminal
handler for this leaf node kind rather than falling through to the generic
recursive descent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_string_literal" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Return
End Process

@Reasoning:
An expandable (double-quoted) string "$x is $($y+1)" contains embedded
variable references and sub-expressions held on the arguments field. Each
embedded fragment is analyzed so the variables it interpolates are checked
for definition.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_expandable_string" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.arguments and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
The generic fallback for any node kind the dispatcher does not handle
explicitly. Performs a structural recursive descent into every child-
bearing field (body, arguments, parameters, pipeline_elements,
param_block) so no part of the tree is skipped. This guarantees variable
and command checks still reach nodes whose kind has no dedicated analyzer.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_generic_powershell_node" that takes node as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.body and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.arguments and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.parameters and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_node_list with node.pipeline_elements and ctx
    Call analyze_powershell_child with node.param_block and ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ATTRIBUTE / SCOPE / COMMAND HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Reports whether the function's attribute list contains a [CmdletBinding()]
attribute, which promotes a simple function to an advanced function with
common parameters and parameter-set binding.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_cmdlet_binding_attribute" that takes attributes as PowerShellSemNode returns Boolean:
    Return powershell_attributes_contain with attributes and "CmdletBinding"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reports whether the attribute list marks the construct as a filter (the
"filter" keyword / [Filter] semantics), which runs the body once per
pipeline element instead of once per invocation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_filter_attribute" that takes attributes as PowerShellSemNode returns Boolean:
    Return powershell_attributes_contain with attributes and "Filter"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reports whether the attribute list marks the construct as a PowerShell
Workflow, which carries parallel/checkpoint execution semantics distinct
from a normal function.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_workflow_attribute" that takes attributes as PowerShellSemNode returns Boolean:
    Return powershell_attributes_contain with attributes and "Workflow"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reports whether a name matches a registered core cmdlet, used to warn when
a user function shadows a built-in. Checks the cmdlet registry directly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_core_cmdlet_name" that takes name as String, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Boolean:
    If ctx.cmdlet_registry contains key name:
        Return true
    End If
    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a PowerShellCmdlet descriptor for a user-defined function so command
resolution can hand command-binding the same record shape it uses for
cmdlets. command_type="Function" routes validation to the function-
parameter checker. The verb is left empty because user functions are not
required to follow Verb-Noun.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_function_cmdlet_info" that takes command_name as String, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns PowerShellCmdlet:
    Return a value of type PowerShellCmdlet with
        name as command_name,
        verb as "",
        noun as "",
        parameters as a list containing nothing,
        parameter_sets as a list containing nothing,
        input_types as a list containing nothing,
        output_types as a list containing nothing,
        module_name as "",
        command_type as "Function",
        help_info as 0,
        is_core_cmdlet as false,
        requires_elevation as false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a PowerShellCmdlet descriptor for an external command (an .exe or
script resolved via PATH). command_type="External" routes validation to the
permissive external-parameter checker since PowerShell cannot statically
know an external program's parameter surface.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_external_command_info" that takes command_name as String returns PowerShellCmdlet:
    Return a value of type PowerShellCmdlet with
        name as command_name,
        verb as "",
        noun as "",
        parameters as a list containing nothing,
        parameter_sets as a list containing nothing,
        input_types as a list containing nothing,
        output_types as a list containing nothing,
        module_name as "",
        command_type as "External",
        help_info as 0,
        is_core_cmdlet as false,
        requires_elevation as false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks the scope chain to the global scope (the one with is_global=true and
no parent). Used to resolve "$global:" scope-modifier references.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_global_scope" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns PowerShellScope:
    Let scope be ctx.current_scope
    While scope is not equal to 0:
        If scope.is_global:
            Return scope
        End If
        If scope.parent_scope is equal to 0:
            Return scope
        End If
        Set scope to scope.parent_scope
    End While
    Return ctx.current_scope
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks the scope chain to the nearest script scope (is_script=true). Used to
resolve "$script:" scope-modifier references. Falls back to the global
scope when no explicit script scope exists.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_script_scope" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns PowerShellScope:
    Let scope be ctx.current_scope
    While scope is not equal to 0:
        If scope.is_script:
            Return scope
        End If
        Set scope to scope.parent_scope
    End While
    Return find_global_scope with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the current scope as the private scope. A "$private:" reference
binds to / reads from the current scope only and must not inherit from
parents, so private lookup is confined to the current scope.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_private_scope" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns PowerShellScope:
    Return ctx.current_scope
End Process

@Reasoning:
Resolves a numbered scope modifier ("$1:" / "$2:") by walking that many
parent links up from the current scope. A 0 modifier means the current
scope; if the chain is shorter than the requested depth, the topmost
reachable scope is returned (matching PowerShell, which clamps to global).
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_numbered_scope" that takes scope_modifier as String, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns PowerShellScope:
    Let depth be string_to_integer_powershell with scope_modifier
    Let scope be ctx.current_scope
    Let steps be 0
    While steps is less than depth:
        If scope.parent_scope is equal to 0:
            Return scope
        End If
        Set scope to scope.parent_scope
        Set steps to steps plus 1
    End While
    Return scope
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a non-negative decimal scope-number string into an Integer. Returns
0 for an empty or non-numeric string. Implements the digit accumulation
directly rather than delegating so scope resolution has no hidden
dependency on a numeric parse primitive's exact name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "string_to_integer_powershell" that takes s as String returns Integer:
    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with s
    Let result be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let c be proc string_char_at from StringCore with s, i
        If c is greater than or equal to 48:
            If c is less than or equal to 57:
                Set result to (result multiplied by 10) plus (c minus 48)
            Otherwise:
                Return result
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Return result
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE INFERENCE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Infers the object type flowing out of a pipeline element. Cmdlet output is
looked up from the resolved cmdlet's declared output_types (first entry);
when a cmdlet declares no output type, or the element is not a cmdlet, the
universal System.Object type is returned so downstream compatibility checks
stay permissive rather than producing false errors.
@End Reasoning
Process called "infer_powershell_output_type" that takes element as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns PowerShellType:
    If element is equal to 0:
        Return create_any_powershell_type
    End If
    Let cmd_name be element.command_name
    If cmd_name is equal to 0:
        Return create_any_powershell_type
    End If
    If ctx.cmdlet_registry contains key cmd_name:
        Let cmd as PowerShellCmdlet be ctx.cmdlet_registry at key cmd_name
        If cmd.output_types is not equal to 0:
            If length of cmd.output_types is greater than 0:
                Let first_type be cmd.output_types at index 0
                Return a value of type PowerShellType with
                    name as first_type,
                    namespace as "System",
                    assembly as "mscorlib",
                    is_value_type as false,
                    is_reference_type as true,
                    is_array as false,
                    is_collection as false,
                    element_type as 0,
                    generic_arguments as 0
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Return create_any_powershell_type
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PARAMETER VALIDATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Validates the named/positional arguments bound to a cmdlet invocation.
For each supplied named parameter it confirms the cmdlet declares a
parameter of that name; an unknown name is a real error. It also confirms
every mandatory declared parameter is satisfied by either a named binding
or a positional argument; an unsatisfied mandatory parameter is a real
error. requires_elevation cmdlets used without an elevation guard produce
a warning.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_cmdlet_parameters" that takes command_info as PowerShellCmdlet, parameters as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If command_info.requires_elevation:
        Let ew be "Cmdlet '" joined with command_info.name joined with "' may require administrator elevation"
        Add ew to end of ctx.warning_list
    End If

    Note: Determine whether this cmdlet carries declared parameter metadata.
    Note: Without it (binary cmdlets registered with name/verb/noun only),
    Note: name-level validation has nothing authoritative to check against.
    Let has_param_metadata be false
    If command_info.parameters is not equal to 0:
        If length of command_info.parameters is greater than 0:
            Set has_param_metadata to true
        End If
    End If

    Note: Validate each supplied named parameter against declared parameters
    If has_param_metadata:
        If parameters is not equal to 0:
            Let supplied_count be length of parameters
            For Each pidx from 0 to (supplied_count minus 1):
                Let supplied as PowerShellSemNode be parameters at index pidx
                If supplied is not equal to 0:
                    Let supplied_name be supplied.name
                    If supplied_name is not equal to 0:
                        Let found be cmdlet_declares_parameter with command_info and supplied_name
                        If found is equal to false:
                            Let perr be "Cmdlet '" joined with command_info.name joined with "' has no parameter named '" joined with supplied_name joined with "'"
                            Add perr to end of ctx.error_list
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End For
        End If
    End If

    Note: Confirm every mandatory declared parameter is provided
    If has_param_metadata:
        Let declared_count be length of command_info.parameters
        For Each didx from 0 to (declared_count minus 1):
            Let declared as PowerShellParameter be command_info.parameters at index didx
            If declared is not equal to 0:
                If declared.is_mandatory:
                    Let provided be parameter_supplied with parameters and declared.name
                    If provided is equal to false:
                        Let merr be "Cmdlet '" joined with command_info.name joined with "' is missing mandatory parameter '" joined with declared.name joined with "'"
                        Add merr to end of ctx.error_list
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End For
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reports whether a cmdlet declares a parameter with the given name, scanning
the cmdlet's declared parameter list. Drives unknown-parameter detection.
@End Reasoning
Process called "cmdlet_declares_parameter" that takes command_info as PowerShellCmdlet, param_name as String returns Boolean:
    If command_info.parameters is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    Let count be length of command_info.parameters
    For Each idx from 0 to (count minus 1):
        Let declared as PowerShellParameter be command_info.parameters at index idx
        If declared is not equal to 0:
            If declared.name is equal to param_name:
                Return true
            End If
        End If
    End For
    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reports whether a parameter of the given name appears among the arguments
actually supplied at a call site. Drives missing-mandatory detection.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parameter_supplied" that takes parameters as PowerShellSemNode, param_name as String returns Boolean:
    If parameters is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    Let count be length of parameters
    For Each idx from 0 to (count minus 1):
        Let supplied as PowerShellSemNode be parameters at index idx
        If supplied is not equal to 0:
            If supplied.name is equal to param_name:
                Return true
            End If
        End If
    End For
    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates arguments bound to a user-defined function. The function's
parameter surface is resolved from the registered PowerShellFunction; each
mandatory parameter must be satisfied by a supplied argument or a real
error is emitted. Unknown named arguments are reported only when the
function declares an explicit param() block (advanced functions),
since simple functions accept arbitrary positional args via $args.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_function_parameters" that takes command_info as PowerShellCmdlet, parameters as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let fname be command_info.name
    If ctx.current_scope.functions contains key fname:
        Let func as PowerShellFunction be ctx.current_scope.functions at key fname
        If func.parameters is not equal to 0:
            Let declared_count be length of func.parameters
            For Each didx from 0 to (declared_count minus 1):
                Let declared as PowerShellParameter be func.parameters at index didx
                If declared is not equal to 0:
                    If declared.is_mandatory:
                        Let provided be parameter_supplied with parameters and declared.name
                        If provided is equal to false:
                            Let merr be "Function '" joined with fname joined with "' is missing mandatory parameter '" joined with declared.name joined with "'"
                            Add merr to end of ctx.error_list
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End For
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates arguments passed through an alias. The alias has already been
resolved to its canonical command upstream in resolve_powershell_command,
so by the time validation runs the command_info describes a cmdlet or
function. This handler therefore re-applies cmdlet parameter validation to
the resolved target so aliased calls are checked identically to direct
ones.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_alias_parameters" that takes command_info as PowerShellCmdlet, parameters as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Call validate_cmdlet_parameters with command_info and parameters and ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates arguments to an external program. PowerShell cannot statically
know an external executable's accepted switches, so the only real check is
that each supplied argument expression is itself well-formed; that
traversal already happens in analyze_powershell_command. A bare external
invocation with no further static contract is therefore accepted without
emitting spurious parameter errors. We still warn when the program name is
empty (an unresolved external command).
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_external_parameters" that takes command_info as PowerShellCmdlet, parameters as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Let ename be command_info.name
    Let ename_len be proc string_length from StringCore with ename
    If ename_len is equal to 0:
        Add "External command invoked with empty name" to end of ctx.warning_list
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PIPELINE / SPLATTING VALIDATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Validates that the object type produced by one pipeline stage is acceptable
input to the next. A producing stage that yields System.Object (the
permissive any-type) is always accepted. When the producer yields a
specific type and the consuming cmdlet declares concrete input_types, the
producer type must appear among them; otherwise a real type-mismatch
warning is emitted. Consumers with no declared input_types accept anything.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_pipeline_compatibility" that takes producer_type as PowerShellType, element as PowerShellSemNode, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If producer_type is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    If producer_type.name is equal to "System.Object":
        Return
    End If
    If element is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let consumer_name be element.command_name
    If consumer_name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    If ctx.cmdlet_registry contains key consumer_name:
        Let consumer as PowerShellCmdlet be ctx.cmdlet_registry at key consumer_name
        If consumer.input_types is not equal to 0:
            Let in_count be length of consumer.input_types
            If in_count is greater than 0:
                Let accepted be false
                For Each idx from 0 to (in_count minus 1):
                    Let in_type be consumer.input_types at index idx
                    If in_type is equal to producer_type.name:
                        Set accepted to true
                    End If
                End For
                If accepted is equal to false:
                    Let pw be "Pipeline type '" joined with producer_type.name joined with "' may not bind to input of '" joined with consumer_name joined with "'"
                    Add pw to end of ctx.warning_list
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates a splatting reference ("@var"). Splatting expands a hashtable or
array variable into a command's parameters. The reference must resolve to a
defined variable; an undefined splat target is a real error because there
is nothing to expand. Splatting an automatic variable other than $args or
$PSBoundParameters is unusual and produces a warning.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_splatting_usage" that takes var_name as String, variable as PowerShellVariable, ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If variable is equal to 0:
        If ctx.automatic_variables contains key var_name:
            Return
        End If
        Let serr be "Splatting variable '" joined with var_name joined with "' is not defined"
        Add serr to end of ctx.error_list
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FINAL-PASS VALIDATORS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Walks every variable bound during analysis (recorded in declared_variables
as each assignment / foreach-binding / parameter-binding occurs) and
reports user-defined variables that were assigned but never read
(last_access_line never advanced beyond first_assignment_line). That
pattern usually indicates dead code or a typo. Automatic variables are
exempt because they exist regardless of use.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_powershell_variable_usage" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If ctx.declared_variables is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be length of ctx.declared_variables
    For Each idx from 0 to (count minus 1):
        Let v as PowerShellVariable be ctx.declared_variables at index idx
        If v is not equal to 0:
            If v.is_automatic is equal to false:
                If v.first_assignment_line is not equal to 0:
                    If v.last_access_line is less than or equal to v.first_assignment_line:
                        Let uw be "Variable '" joined with v.name joined with "' is assigned but never read"
                        Add uw to end of ctx.warning_list
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Walks the functions defined during analysis (recorded in declared_functions
at each function-definition site) and warns about advanced functions
declared with [CmdletBinding()] that follow no Verb-Noun naming convention.
Advanced functions are intended to behave like cmdlets and PowerShell's own
analyzer flags non-Verb-Noun advanced-function names, so this reproduces
that real lint.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_powershell_function_usage" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If ctx.declared_functions is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be length of ctx.declared_functions
    For Each idx from 0 to (count minus 1):
        Let func as PowerShellFunction be ctx.declared_functions at index idx
        If func is not equal to 0:
            If func.is_advanced:
                Let is_vn be powershell_is_verb_noun_shape with func.name
                If is_vn is equal to false:
                    Let fw be "Advanced function '" joined with func.name joined with "' does not follow Verb-Noun naming"
                    Add fw to end of ctx.warning_list
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reviews every command invocation seen in the AST (recorded in
invoked_commands during analyze_powershell_command). Any invocation that
resolved to an External command type was not found among loaded cmdlets,
functions, or aliases, so it is reported as an unresolved command — a real
finding that PowerShell would surface as "command not recognized" unless
the program is on PATH at run time.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_powershell_cmdlet_usage" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If ctx.invoked_commands is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be length of ctx.invoked_commands
    For Each idx from 0 to (count minus 1):
        Let cmd as PowerShellCmdlet be ctx.invoked_commands at index idx
        If cmd is not equal to 0:
            If cmd.command_type is equal to "External":
                Let cw be "Command '" joined with cmd.name joined with "' did not resolve to a known cmdlet, function, or alias"
                Add cw to end of ctx.warning_list
            End If
        End If
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reviews every multi-stage pipeline stage observed during analysis
(recorded in pipeline_stages). A stage that resolved to an External
command type is an unresolved cmdlet inside a pipeline, which more often
indicates a typo than an intentional external call (PowerShell pipelines
usually chain cmdlets), so each such stage is reported as a real warning.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_powershell_pipeline_usage" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If ctx.pipeline_stages is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be length of ctx.pipeline_stages
    For Each idx from 0 to (count minus 1):
        Let stage as PowerShellCmdlet be ctx.pipeline_stages at index idx
        If stage is not equal to 0:
            If stage.command_type is equal to "External":
                Let pw be "Pipeline stage '" joined with stage.name joined with "' did not resolve to a known cmdlet or function"
                Add pw to end of ctx.warning_list
            End If
        End If
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Enforces execution-policy consistency. Under a "Restricted" policy no
scripts may run, so a script that defined any functions (evidence of real
script content) is flagged: it cannot execute under Restricted and the
author likely needs RemoteSigned or Bypass. The defined-function evidence
comes from the declared_functions list populated during analysis.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_powershell_execution_policy" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    If ctx.execution_policy is equal to "Restricted":
        Let has_content be false
        If ctx.declared_functions is not equal to 0:
            If length of ctx.declared_functions is greater than 0:
                Set has_content to true
            End If
        End If
        If has_content:
            Add "Script defines functions but execution policy is Restricted; script cannot run as-is" to end of ctx.warning_list
        End If
    End If
End Process

Note: Entry point for PowerShell semantic analysis
@Reasoning:
Thin wrapper over analyze_powershell_semantics that exposes a stable
public name (matches the analyze_*_semantic_tree convention used across
the other language frontends).
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_powershell_semantic_tree" that takes ast as PowerShellSemNode returns PowerShellSemanticContext:
    Return analyze_powershell_semantics with ast
End Process